  "prompt": "What is the difference between '-' and '-=' operators in C++?",
  "response": "In C++, both `-` and `-=` are operators, but they serve different purposes and are used in different contexts. Here\u2019s a detailed explanation of each:\n\n1. **`-` (Subtraction Operator):**\n   - The `-` operator is a binary arithmetic operator used to subtract one value from another.\n   - It takes two operands and returns the result of their subtraction.\n   - Example:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     int b = 3;\n     int result = a - b;  // result is 7\n     ```\n\n2. **`-=` (Subtraction Assignment Operator):**\n   - The `-=` operator is a compound assignment operator that combines subtraction with assignment.\n   - It subtracts the right-hand operand from the left-hand operand and then assigns the result back to the left-hand operand.\n   - This operator modifies the value of the left-hand operand directly.\n   - Example:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     a -= 3;  // Equivalent to a = a - 3; Now a is 7\n     ```\n\n### Summary:\n- **`-`**: Used for simple subtraction between two values.\n- **`-=`**: Used to subtract a value from a variable and update the variable with the result in one step.\n\nBoth operators are essential for arithmetic operations, but `-=` is particularly useful for updating variables concisely within loops or other control structures.",
